      "summary": "Three.js ShaderMaterial with custom GLSL vertex + fragment shaders to replicate PlayStation 1 (PS1) rendering artifacts. Key effects: vertex wobble (integer-snapping world-space positions to emulate low-precision affine texture mapping), color quantization (reduce 24-bit color to 15-bit/16-bit via banding in fragment shader), shadow tint #003344 applied as ambient occlusion multiplier in fragment output. The ShaderMaterial bypasses Three.js PBR pipeline, applying a raw unlit look consistent with PS1-era Gouraud shading. Pixel block size of 4-16px is achieved by rendering to a smaller off-screen RenderTarget then upscaling with nearest-neighbor filtering — the PRD's `pixel_block_size` parameter controls render target divisor. All 4 liminal-space scenes share ps1_vertex.glsl and ps1_fragment.glsl as their material shaders. Feasibility: PASS — Three.js natively supports ShaderMaterial with custom GLSL, and this approach is widely demonstrated in retro-shader community projects.",
